Airports Company South Africa broke records and achieved a historic milestone last year with its network of nine airports reaching and passing the 39 million passenger mark for the year.At the end of December, 39.7 million passengers had been facilitated, a 5.4% increase from 2015. The three main international gateways achieved firsts with OR Tambo International Airport exceeding 20 million passengers, Cape Town International Airport processing 10 million passengers and King Shaka International Airport processing more than 5 million passengers for the year.King Shaka recorded the highest overall growth with an 8.45% increase, Cape Town was second at 7.3% and OR Tambo saw a 3.8% increase. Domestic arrivals rose to 13.6 million passengers, an increase of 5.3% from the previous year. Domestic departures also experienced an increase with 13.7 million passengers, a 5.3% increase from 2015.International arrivals increased by 5.3% with 5.4 million passengers while international departures rose by a notable 5.8% to 5.5 million passengers. Regional travel to neighbouring countries, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho and Swaziland, remained healthy with regional arrivals going up by 6% to 567 254 passengers, while regional departures went up 6.4% with 565 702 passengers due to the festive season.Domestic traffic growth in the fourth quarter of 2016 slowed down, with arrivals only increasing by 1.4% and departures only going up by a marginal 1.2% compared to the same period in 2015. The strongest driver of passenger growth in the final quarter was international departures, which saw a growth of 7.5% and international arrivals with a recorded 7.1% increase.This was due to the summer holidays, which is traditionally one of the busiest travel seasons in the country.-Sello Rabothata|sellor@thenewage.co.za